{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"78be430b-4e0f-466c-a2a2-35c97fb0a863","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS. You must set `ulimit -c unlimited` **before** running the app.\n\n**Quick check:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/ | head\n```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries — often sufficient for diagnosing the issue without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bec19c01-973d-465c-84b2-05e1c31bbdf5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":308,"requestId":"640E:3ED481:14FC52B:187B2E0:69EC19C7"},"id":"b01f4016-7bc6-4276-a041-ab98f7429e0b","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:33:03.791Z","parentId":"689cb436-50fa-4c6c-972e-b414fe0829cf"}
